105 million PLN for video games companies from the National Research and Development Centre
Almost PLN 105 million of funding will reach companies in the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Research and Development Centre announced on Friday the results of the third edition of the GameINN programme.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by the NCBR, for example, was the development of a platform to create field games based on the AR game engine, creating a real world map along with an application to enable users to transmit data; a test-and-training platform to verify practical skills in the position of work and professional improvement using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game to simulate the management of real production processes using a innovative game model based on virtual world interaction with the real world using industry 4.0 – the communication of the NCBR sent on Friday.
The objective of the GameINN Sector Programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry on the global market in the future by 2023.
According to the NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video market in 2016 was PLN 1.85 billion and the forecast for 2019 was PLN 2.23 billion.
"The Specially Prepared GameINN Research Agenda, which is already 300 million PLN of support for entrepreneurs under this sectoral programme, is an important impetus for the further dynamic growth of the Polish gamedev," we read in the Communication.
The video gaming industry is an excellent example of the effective use of the potential that we have in Poland.
"The incentives put in place by the government for innovative entrepreneurs, such as R & D facilities, competence improvement programmes, IP boxes or support programmes implemented by the NCBR, drive the innovative activities of companies and allow them to compete more effectively on a highly competitive market," said Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the Communication.
The head of the science department points out that the money for innovation not only goes to the innovators in the form of project funding, but also remains in their pockets – three quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R & D in 2018 than they did a year ago.
"The amount of the deducted costs for R & D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in more than PLN 300 million in savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in the three editions of GameINN," stresses the Deputy Prime Minister.
The director of the NCBR, Wojciech Kamieenecki, recalls that in the previous two funding competitions of a total of more than PLN 211.2 million, 78 were awarded to innovative projects.
A huge interest in the III competition and the diversity of proposals made show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
"It is particularly encouraging that projects selected, as in previous editions, include projects on solutions for not only entertainment but also industry-related 4.0," he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, up to PLN 20 million could be applied for by entrepreneurs, a consortium of entrepreneurs and a consortium of entrepreneurs with scientific units.
The NCBR received 87 applications for a total of PLN 317 million.
The competition budget at the time of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, making it possible for 27 projects to receive almost PLN 105 million of funding.
Detailed information on the results of GameINN III is available on the website ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN Sector Programme is implemented under the Smart Development Operational Programme.
The NCBR launched the programme in 2016 in response to the initiative of the Polish Games Associated Entrepreneurs, which includes companies such as CD Project, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team or 11 bit studios.
