GUS: Poland is getting better
A report published Friday by the GUS on household budgets shows that as a good or rather good situation, up to 44% of them assessed their material situation.
The previous year this percentage was 37.2%, in 2016 33.5%, and earlier, since 2009, when the statistical office first examined the subjective assessments of the household situation, it never exceeded 30%.
A total of 8.1 per cent of households considered their material situation to be bad or rather bad compared to 11.2 per cent earlier and more than 20 per cent in 2009.
The best situation is the material situation of households of self-employed people.
In this group, over 70% of respondents consider it good or rather good.
On the second pole there are households of renaissants, where the percentage of such responses was only 18%.
The number of children also has a major impact on the subjective assessment of the material situation of households.
Parents who raise their offspring alone know the worst, of which 32 percent declare a good or rather good material situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55% to 60%, and among childrenless households 48.8%.
These statistics clearly show the effect of the 500+ programme.
Before it was launched (in 2016) the worst material situation was assessed by single parents and multi-parent families (with at least three children).
To improve the subjective assessment of the material situation of Poles is to reflect rapid income growth, primarily from work.
That is not all, however, because the percentage of households that consider their situation to be good increases faster than real income.
Moreover, at voivodship level there is no clear link between income levels and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best estimates are formulated by Opolska voivodship residents, where 48.9% of the respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
There are still Lubuskie voivodships (47.7%), Silesian (47.6%), Mazowieckie (47.3%) and Western Pomeranian (47.1%).
Meanwhile, in Opolski, the administrative income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) was below 94% of the national average and in Lubusk 98%.
The highest incomes were the inhabitants of Mazowiecki (120% of the national average) and Silesia (104%).
On average, in Poland, the revenue per person was PLN 1693.
In real terms (after the price adjustment) it increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Back in the last few years, it's a pretty low score.
In 2016, income per person increased by 7% and a year later by 6.3%.
While income growth slows down, it also inhibits spending growth.
These per person amounted to PLN 1187, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person actually increased by 1.9% and in 2016 by 4.3%.
Household budget surveys suggest that the statistical household currently spends 70.1% of its regulatory revenue, while in 2014 it exceeded 80% and by 2006 it exceeded 90%.
