"Richpopolita": Ignoring a police officer's order will be punished
According to the paper, disregarding a specific order issued by a police officer is intended to be a new type of offence, threatened by a fine, arrest or restriction of liberty.
Police unionists want to make such a change.
The idea came to the petition committee's meeting.
"The case is serious, because more than half a million crimes are already being brought to Polish courts every year," we read.
The ‘Rzeczpospolita’ found that the petition that the Independent Police Union wrote to the Members on the amendment of the Code of Offences had a chance of success.
The petitioners propose the new wording of Article 54a of the Code of Offences.
It would read: ‘Whoever is not subject to the request or order of a public official issued within the limits and on the basis of the provisions of the law is subject to the penalty of arrest, fine or restriction of liberty’.
"Paragraph 3 of this provision speaks of the same punishment for those who do not follow orders, prevent or make it difficult to perform their duties," the journal states.
Sociologist Andrzej Kowalski said "The Republic" that although he agrees with the main message of the proposal, he fears that if implemented, it can be used in political manifestations.
"In situations of free demonstration, it would be unfavourable and, instead of mitigating the situation, would even exacerbate it," he adds.
Statistics provided by the newspaper show that 86% of citizens have positively assessed police intervention in 2018 and that they take 1.5 million interventions in the city each month.
