Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancelled 105 flights due to Thomas Cook bankruptcy
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has fallen, his Belgian subsidiary Neckermann is functioning.
However, the company has problems.
According to VRT, Brussels Airlines announced that they would cancel 105 flights in October due to bankruptcy problems related to Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also fired 75 employees.
All departures with the office that have been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but the timers will be able to receive a refund.
The court in Gandhi also announced the bankruptcy of three Belgian subsidiaries: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently, about 12,000 Belgians are abroad on the trips bought at Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were to leave the office by the end of the year.
As of Monday, spokesperson Thomas Cook Belgium Leen Segers said that the company is now "fully operational" despite the announcement of bankruptcy by the British company's mother, which caused concern among employees and customers.
The office was then calmed down that the customers who bought the tours in it would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook – the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world – declared bankruptcy on the night of Sunday on Monday.
The direct cause of bankruptcy was the collapse on Sunday of the last chance talks with creditors and potential investors.
Believers demanded that, in addition to the 900 million-pound rescue plan already agreed in August, the company obtain an additional 200 million as a winter insurance when travel agencies usually have lower turnovers.
However, the company’s problems have grown for several years, resulting in a debt of £1.6 billion.
