Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for the review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an extraordinary offer was prepared for the arrival of German Görlitz.
Actions are designed to help combat the gradual decline in the number of people living in the city.
Görlitz is the eastmost city of Germany.
A beautiful pastel old lady attracts 140,000 tourists a year.
However, according to The Guardian, the city is facing significant challenges.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city is also struggling with a constant loss of population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left to the west of the country, which resulted in a 25 percent drop in the city’s population.
In 2013, it amounted to 54,000.
To combat the population, officials came up with the idea of offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been made to the programme.
Two thirds of them built large cities.
The program was also attended by people from Hungary, Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom.
"When we applied, we thought the program was to convince people to move to Görlitz," said one of the participants.
"Now we feel it doesn't matter whether we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has seven thousand vacant apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the average in the whole country.
Although the city authorities hope that some will be held permanently, the main objective of the programme is to get an opinion from the programme participants.
Information collected from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to know more about what people need and if they decide to move – what their motivation was," said Robert Knippschild.
Other cities have already experimented with the idea of attracting new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a programme to pay promising young professionals for their lives and jobs in the city for a year.
Today such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in the U.S. state of Oklahoma.
